{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487067","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487067"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:56:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:56:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"243"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582500"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:44:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:44:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"243"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/243"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.51,0.06,0.03,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"243"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98608"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"243","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/243"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"243"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81007"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"141"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31284"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33442"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42037"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42985"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98608"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after sustaining a fracture to her left neck of femur following a fall from standing height. A total hip replacement is performed. She is usually independent at home and mobilises with a four-wheel walker. Her medical history includes hypercholesterolaemia, epilepsy, urinary incontinence, oesophageal dysmotility, hypertension, a previous provoked above-knee deep vein thrombosis ten years ago, and excision of a squamous cell carcinoma from her face. Her current medications include rosuvastatin, levetiracetam, perindopril, calcium/colecalciferol, and oxybutynin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA bone densitometry (DEXA) scan one year ago showed a T-score of -2.0 at the femoral neck. Her current thyroid function tests and vitamin D and calcium levels are within normal range.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate choice for fracture prevention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Risedronate","Denosumab","Calcium/colecalciferol only","Hip protectors","Raloxifene"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has sustained a fragility fracture; she now has a diagnosis of osteoporosis, irrespective of her bone mineral density T-scores (which in these case would be considered osteopenic). She requires anti-resorptive therapy to reduce her future fracture risk. \u003Cstrong\u003EDenosumab\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice of anti-resorptive therapy of the options presented. Denosumab is a monoclonal antibody against RANK ligand. It is given as a 6-monthly subcutaneous injection that can be continued for up to ten years, after which point transition to an alternative anti-resorptive agent should strongly be considered under specialist guidance. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERisedronate\u003C/strong\u003E is a bisphosphonate that is typically used as a first-line treatment for osteoporosis. However, it can cause oesophagitis, making it unsuitable for patients with oesophageal disorders, such as this patient with oesophageal dysmotility.Intravenous zoledronic acid would, however, be a suitable option. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium/colecalciferol\u003C/strong\u003E supplementation is important for bone health but is not sufficient as a standalone treatment for fracture prevention in patients with osteopaenia or osteoporosis. Additional anti-resorptive therapy is necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHip protectors\u003C/strong\u003E have not been shown to effectively reduce the incidence of hip fractures in community-dwelling elderly individuals. They may be more beneficial in institutionalised settings but are not a substitute for pharmacological treatment in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERaloxifene\u003C/strong\u003E is a selective oestrogen receptor modulator (SERM) that can be used for osteoporosis but carries a risk of thromboembolic events. Given this patient\u0027s history of deep vein thrombosis, raloxifene would not be an appropriate choice. Equally, raloxifene has better evidence in postmenopausal women at high risk of \u003Cem\u003Evertebral\u003C/em\u003E fractures if other therapies like bisphosphonates or denosumab are not tolerated. This is especially the case for younger postmenopausal women with a prior or family history of breast cancer due to its selective antagonistic effects at the breast.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Denosumab can provide effective treatment for osteoporosis in patients with upper gastrointestinal disorders."],"references":["Cummings SR, Martin JS, McClung MR, Siris ES, Eastell R, Reid IR, Delmas P, Zoog HB, Austin M, Wang A, Kutilek S, Adami S, Zanchetta J, Libanati C, Siddhanti S \u0026 Christiansen C (2009). Denosumab for Prevention of Fractures in Postmenopausal Women with Osteoporosis. N Engl J Med 361, 756-765.","Eastell R, Rosen CJ, Black DM, et al. Pharmacological Management of Osteoporosis in Postmenopausal Women: An Endocrine Society Clinical Practice Guideline. J Clin Endocrinol Metab 2019; 104:1595-1622.","Santesso N, Carrasco\u2010Labra A \u0026 Brignardello\u2010Petersen R (2014). Hip protectors for preventing hip fractures in older people. Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews","The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners and Osteoporosis Australia. Osteoporosis prevention, diagnosis and management in postmenopausal women and men over 50 years of age. 2nd edn. East Melbourne, Vic: RACGP, 2017","The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. \u201cOsteoporosis Management and Fracture Prevention in Post-Menopausal Women and Men \u003E 50 Years of Age \u2013 Summary of Recommendations.\u201d RACGP, 2024, www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/osteoporosis/summary-of-recommendations. Accessed 14 Apr. 2025.","Vogel VG. The NSABP Study of Tamoxifen and Raloxifene (STAR) trial. Expert Rev Anticancer Ther. 2009 Jan;9(1):51-60. doi: 10.1586/14737140.9.1.51. Erratum in: Expert Rev Anticancer Ther. 2009 Mar;9(3):388. PMID: 19105706; PMCID: PMC2785111."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81007"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"243"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"81007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/81007"},"attr